"></iframe>
    </div>

    <div id="cardio-view-evidence" style="display:none">
    <div class="cx">
      <p class="cx-lede">When a patient is short of breath, the heart is only half the picture. A complete PFT &mdash; done in-office in about 15&ndash;20 minutes &mdash; rules the lungs in or out on the same visit. Every figure below is drawn from cited peer-reviewed sources and society guidelines a physician can verify.</p>

      <div class="cx-stats">
        <div class="cx-stat"><div class="cx-big">25&ndash;50%</div><div class="cx-lbl">of heart failure patients also have COPD on spirometry &mdash; largely undiagnosed</div></div>
        <div class="cx-stat"><div class="cx-big">~&#189;</div><div class="cx-lbl">of PH-in-HFpEF patients have a DLCO below 45% predicted &mdash; only a full PFT captures it</div></div>
        <div class="cx-stat"><div class="cx-big">15&ndash;20 min</div><div class="cx-lbl">for a complete in-office PFT: spirometry + lung volumes + DLCO</div></div>
      </div>

      <div class="cx-sec">
        <div class="cx-sec-title">Where PFTs change the cardiology workup</div>
        <div class="cx-grid2">
          <div class="cx-card">
            <h4>Sort cardiac vs. pulmonary dyspnea</h4>
            <p>Cardiac and pulmonary disease are the likeliest causes of breathlessness. Spirometry is a recommended <b>first-line</b> test in the chronic-dyspnea workup &mdash; the pulmonary half no longer waits on a referral.</p>
            <span class="cx-src">Source: Chronic Dyspnea: Diagnosis and Evaluation, Am Fam Physician 2020;101(9):542&ndash;548.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="cx-card">
            <h4>Untangle heart failure and COPD</h4>
            <p>On spirometry, COPD is found in roughly <b>25&ndash;50%</b> of heart failure patients and is severely underdiagnosed. <span class="cx-note">HF congestion can cause a reversible obstruction, so a PFT helps separate and co-manage &mdash; not a standalone COPD diagnosis.</span></p>
            <span class="cx-src">Sources: HF &amp; COPD review (PMC12250576); airflow obstruction in stable systolic HF (PMC5219786).</span>
          </div>
          <div class="cx-card">
            <h4>Stratify peri-procedural risk</h4>
            <p>Abnormal pulmonary function is associated with more postoperative pulmonary complications after cardiac surgery. A PFT gives a baseline that helps <b>stratify risk</b> &mdash; a signal, not a pass/fail gate.</p>
            <span class="cx-src">Sources: PFT in preoperative high-risk patients, Perioper Med 2024 (PMC10913451); cardiac-surgery spirometry (PMC7682508).</span>
          </div>
          <div class="cx-card">
            <h4>Monitor cardiotoxic therapy &amp; drug-induced PH</h4>
            <p>The 2022 ESC cardio-oncology guidelines address monitoring for drug-induced pulmonary hypertension (notably dasatinib) &mdash; a targeted surveillance role, not routine screening.</p>
            <span class="cx-src">Source: 2022 ESC Guidelines on Cardio-Oncology, Eur Heart J 2022;43(41):4229&ndash;4361.</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cx-dlco">
          <span class="cx-pill">The full-PFT difference</span>
          <h4>DLCO &mdash; the reason a spirometer isn&rsquo;t enough</h4>
          <p>A plain spirometer measures airflow only. A <b>complete PFT</b> adds lung volumes and <b>DLCO</b> (diffusing capacity), which reflects the gas-exchange surface and pulmonary vasculature &mdash; exactly where cardiac disease shows up in the lungs. In pulmonary hypertension due to <b>HFpEF</b>, nearly half of patients have a DLCO below 45% predicted, and reduced DLCO is associated with higher mortality.</p>
          <span class="cx-src">Sources: Diffusion capacity &amp; mortality in PH due to HFpEF, JACC: Heart Failure 2016; DLCO prognostic value in PH (PMC6935895).</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="cx-sec">
        <div class="cx-sec-title">What a complete PFT bills &mdash; in your office</div>
        <table class="cx-bill">
          <thead><tr><th>CPT</th><th>Component</th><th>Nat&rsquo;l avg</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td class="code">94010</td><td>Spirometry</td><td>$27.34</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="code">94726</td><td>Lung volumes (plethysmography)</td><td>$55.72</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="code">94729</td><td>DLCO (diffusing capacity)</td><td>$59.87</td></tr>
            <tr class="total"><td></td><td>Complete PFT, per patient</td><td>~$151.45</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p class="cx-disc" style="margin-top:8px;"><b>Add-ons when medically necessary:</b> 94060 pre/post bronchodilator ($38.80) &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; 94375 flow-volume loop ($39.11). Billed under the practice &mdash; the study and the revenue stay in-house. Figures are CMS national averages, consistent with the toolkit&rsquo;s single-source rates; confirm against the current CMS fee schedule (updates each January).</p>
      </div>

      <div class="cx-sec">
        <div class="cx-sec-title">Files &amp; templates</div>
        <div class="cx-files">
          <div class="cx-file-row">
            <span class="cx-fname">&#128196; Pulmonary Function in the Cardiology Clinic &mdash; clinical + billing one-pager</span>
            <button class="cx-btn" onclick="m3View('cardio-onepager')">View</button>
            <button class="cx-btn" onclick="m3Download('cardio-onepager')">Download</button>
            <button class="cx-btn primary" onclick="cardioEmailAll()">&#9993; Email it</button>
          </div>
          <p class="cx-disc">This one-pager is also in the <b>Forms</b> tab (Materials Library) and the <b>Email Library</b> as a &#10084; Cardiology quick-pack, plus two ready cardiology email templates (intro &amp; follow-up).</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="cx-disc"><b>Billing &amp; coding:</b> CPT coding should be based on medical necessity; reimbursement is subject to specific health-plan policy. All figures are national averages for informational discussion only. Device timing (~15&ndash;20 min complete PFT) reflects PulmOne product materials. Not a substitute for clinical judgment.</p>
    </div>
    </div><!-- /cardio-view-evidence -->
  </div>

  <div class="tab-panel" id="tab-clinical">
