  <!-- COACHING -->
  <div class="tab-panel" id="tab-coaching">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-icon icon-blue">&#127915;</div>
      <div>
        <div class="section-title">Patient Coaching Quick Reference</div>
        <div class="section-sub">Setup, technique, and what to watch for during each test</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="alert-box alert-blue">
      <div class="alert-icon">&#9432;</div>
      <div><strong>Universal setup for LVM and DLCO:</strong> HHU attached to MiniBox+. Adjust device height for patient. Lips sealed tightly over mouthpiece, teeth over mouthpiece, nose clip applied.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="coaching-card">
      <div class="coaching-header">
        <span class="coaching-tag tag-fvc">FVC</span>
        <div>
          <div class="coaching-name">Forced Vital Capacity</div>
          <div class="coaching-desc">HHU detached from MiniBox+ for zeroing &mdash; then handed to patient. ATS requires 3 to 8 efforts.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="coaching-body">
        <div>
          <div class="coaching-col-title">Setup</div>
          <ul class="coaching-list">
            <li><div class="cli-num">1</div> Detach HHU from MiniBox+ and allow to calibrate (zeroing).</li>
            <li><div class="cli-num">2</div> Hand HHU to patient. Seal lips around mouthpiece, teeth over it, apply nose clip.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="coaching-col-title">Coaching the Patient</div>
          <ul class="coaching-list">
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> Start with 2 to 3 normal relaxed breaths.</li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> <span class="highlight">Deep inhale, then immediate forced fast exhale.</span></li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> <span class="highlight">Squeeze ALL air out until the wheel turns GREEN.</span></li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> Deep breath back in to close the flow volume loop.</li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> Coach them to "BLAST" not just "blow." Prompt the sharp start &mdash; no hesitation at top of inhale.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="coaching-card">
      <div class="coaching-header">
        <span class="coaching-tag tag-lvm">LVM</span>
        <div>
          <div class="coaching-name">Lung Volume Measurement</div>
          <div class="coaching-desc">HHU attached to MiniBox+. Must be performed after FVC. Counter must reach SIX successful events.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="coaching-body">
        <div>
          <div class="coaching-col-title">Setup</div>
          <ul class="coaching-list">
            <li><div class="cli-num">1</div> Attach HHU to MiniBox+. Adjust device height for patient.</li>
            <li><div class="cli-num">2</div> Patient seals lips and applies nose clip.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="coaching-col-title">Coaching the Patient</div>
          <ul class="coaching-list">
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> Relaxed normal breathing for about one minute. <span class="highlight">Keep breaths below 1 Liter.</span></li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> <span class="highlight">Once counter turns GREEN and reads "6,"</span> on the NEXT breath take a slow deep inhale to full capacity.</li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> Breathe out slow, squeeze all air out until the line hits plateau (empty).</li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> Take a breath in and come off mouthpiece.</li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> Watch for downward or upward sloping graph &mdash; indicates air leak.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="coaching-card">
      <div class="coaching-header">
        <span class="coaching-tag tag-dlco">DLCO</span>
        <div>
          <div class="coaching-name">Diffusing Capacity</div>
          <div class="coaching-desc">HHU attached. Minimum 2, maximum 5 tests. Allow 4 minutes between tests for gas clearance.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="coaching-body">
        <div>
          <div class="coaching-col-title">Setup</div>
          <ul class="coaching-list">
            <li><div class="cli-num">1</div> Attach HHU to MiniBox+. Adjust height. Patient seals lips, applies nose clip.</li>
            <li><div class="cli-num">2</div> Start on an inhale and complete <span class="highlight">FOUR normal tidal breaths.</span></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="coaching-col-title">Coaching the Patient</div>
          <ul class="coaching-list">
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> Patient exhales fully on the 4th breath.</li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> <span class="highlight">Wait for device to click (valve closes),</span> then take a fast deep breath in to TLC.</li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> <span class="highlight">Inhalation must reach above the GREEN dotted line.</span> Patient should inhale 85% of VC within 4 seconds.</li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> <span class="highlight">Hold breath for 8 to 10 seconds.</span></li>
            <li><div class="cli-dot">&#8226;</div> Once wheel turns GREEN, exhale completely to empty. Then inhale and come off mouthpiece.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-icon icon-amber">&#9888;</div>
      <div>
        <div class="section-title">Common Failure Reasons &amp; Fixes</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card-grid grid-2">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title" style="color:#c0392b;">FVC &mdash; "Don't hesitate, exhale faster"</div>
        <div class="card-body">Patient paused at the top of the inhalation (Evol exceeded 5% of FVC). Fix: coach them to <strong>immediately blast</strong> the air out the moment they reach peak inhalation &mdash; zero hesitation.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title" style="color:#c0392b;">FVC &mdash; End-of-test criteria not found</div>
        <div class="card-body">Patient stopped exhaling before the plateau was reached. Fix: <strong>"Keep going, blow out every last bit of air."</strong> Common in COPD patients who have prolonged expiratory time.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title" style="color:#c0392b;">LVM &mdash; TGV line not established</div>
        <div class="card-body">Tidal breathing was irregular before the maneuver. Fix: <strong>delete this test result</strong> (manual specifically recommends it). Allow patient to settle and breathe normally before restarting.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title" style="color:#c0392b;">DLCO &mdash; Couldn't find stable parameters</div>
        <div class="card-body">The 4 required tidal breaths were skipped or unsteady. Fix: reinforce the sequence. <strong>Do NOT rush</strong> the patient into the maneuver. Wait the full 4 minutes before repeating.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- INTERPRETATION -->
  <div class="tab-panel" id="tab-interpretation">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-icon icon-teal">&#129504;</div>
      <div>
        <div class="section-title">Interpreting PFT Results</div>
        <div class="section-sub">A stepwise clinical approach authored by Jeffrey Weiss, MD &mdash; Weiss Medical Allergy, Asthma &amp; Immunology</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="alert-box alert-blue">
      <div class="alert-icon">&#9432;</div>
      <div>The MiniBox+ automatically generates an ATS/ERS-based interpretation and decision tree with every report. The following is the clinical logic behind it. <strong>Physician review is always required.</strong></div>
    </div>

    <div class="interp-step">
      <div class="step-num-big">1</div>
      <div class="interp-text"><strong>Look at spirometry first.</strong> Normal or abnormal FEV1. If abnormal, look for other signs of an obstructive ventilatory defect: low FEF 25-75 and low FEV1/FVC.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="interp-step">
      <div class="step-num-big">2</div>
      <div class="interp-text"><strong>If FVC is low,</strong> this could be a sign of a restrictive ventilatory defect. Check PEF to evaluate the effort of the maneuver.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="interp-step">
      <div class="step-num-big">3</div>
      <div class="interp-text"><strong>If clinical history suggests asthma,</strong> administer a bronchodilator and check for a bronchodilator response (12% improvement in FEV1 or 20% improvement in FEF25-75). You can also perform methacholine challenge &mdash; a 15 to 20% decrease in FEV1 from the provocative dose is significant.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="interp-step">
      <div class="step-num-big">4</div>
      <div class="interp-text"><strong>If FEV1 is normal but you're still concerned,</strong> check Lung Volumes next. If RV is elevated, this suggests air trapping &mdash; which could indicate an obstructive ventilatory defect (e.g. asthma).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="interp-step">
      <div class="step-num-big">5</div>
      <div class="interp-text"><strong>If lung volumes show a decrease in TLC,</strong> this is indicative of a restrictive ventilatory defect.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="interp-step">
      <div class="step-num-big">6</div>
      <div class="interp-text"><strong>If restriction is confirmed,</strong> check DLCO to determine the cause. Normal DLCO suggests extra-parenchymal processes (outside the lungs) such as a neuromuscular disorder. Low DLCO suggests an intra-parenchymal process (within the lungs) such as interstitial lung disease, idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, sarcoidosis, or emphysema.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-icon icon-teal">&#127775;</div>
      <div>
        <div class="section-title">DLCO Clinical Pearls</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card-grid grid-2">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title" style="color:#c0392b;">Low DLCO &mdash; Think</div>
        <div class="card-body">Emphysema, Interstitial Lung Disease (ILD), Idiopathic Pulmonary Fibrosis, Sarcoidosis, Pulmonary Vascular disease, Anemia, Early emphysema, Early ILD. Also present in COVID-related lung damage and COPD.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title" style="color:#27ae60;">High DLCO &mdash; Think</div>
        <div class="card-body">Asthma, Obesity, Polycythemia, Intrapulmonary Hemorrhage. A high DLCO in context of obstruction often points toward asthma rather than emphysema.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title">Normal Spirometry + Low DLCO</div>
        <div class="card-body">May suggest Anemia, Pulmonary Vascular Disorders, Early ILD, or Early Emphysema. Lung volumes are normal but gas transfer is impaired &mdash; catch this early before spirometry changes.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title">Emphysema Pattern</div>
        <div class="card-body">Can present with airflow obstruction on PFTs <strong>AND</strong> low DLCO simultaneously. This combination is a key differentiator from asthma, where DLCO is typically normal or elevated.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <div class="alert-box alert-amber">
      <div class="alert-icon">&#128161;</div>
      <div><strong>Why LVM matters for allergists and pulmonologists:</strong> Spirometry can appear normal even when air trapping is occurring. An elevated RV (residual volume) on the LVM test is the earliest indicator of obstructive disease &mdash; especially in asthma where the FEV1 may still be within normal range. This is a compelling reason to add LVM to every spirometry encounter.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

